    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov 24 1873</date>
                    <salute>My dear George</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>You have been a v. good man to send us so long a letter, which has amused us all.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> I am greatly pleased that you will undertake the Descent.<ref target="#foot.f2"/> I don’t think I shall have any part ready for 1 or 2 months. It is an <hi rend="doubleUnderline">awful</hi> job, not so much from the quantity which I shall write, as in consulting books &amp; reading old letters   I doubt whether I shall be able to let you have any till all is completed. There will be no occasion for you to hurry, as the public must wait for the copies which Murray has sold.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> I will give you 2 cautions, viz. not to alter the strength of my expressions &amp; 2<hi rend="superscript">ndly</hi> not to improve my style too much, as I deliberately think that it is best for each man to retain his own style, &amp; that rather rugged sentences do not signify, if they are perfectly clear (i.e. as unlike Snow’s as possible.)<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.4 old] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> <hi rend="italic">in CD’s hand</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9157F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from G. H. Darwin to Emma Darwin, [before 24 November 1873]</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_1224.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">George Howard Darwin</ref> had agreed to undertake the work to produce a second edition of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref>, detailed in the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9157.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to G. H. Darwin, 20 November 1873</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD’s publisher, John Murray, had printed a further 1000 copies of <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1966.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Descent</hi></ref> in December 1871, bringing the total to 8000 (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 19, <ref target="./DCP-LETT-8074.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to R. F. Cooke, 17 November 1871</ref>, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2661.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Freeman 1977</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD refers to his niece Frances Julia Wedgwood (known as Snow), whose style had been criticised ‘as wanting in simplicity &amp; too full of allusion, not distinctly explained’ (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 16, enclosure to <ref target="./DCP-LETT-6207.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to John Murray, 25 May 1868</ref>). See also <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9157F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from G. H. Darwin to Emma Darwin, [before 24 November 1873]</ref> and n. 9.</note>
        </div>        
            
